oneOf.description: The default place mode. This mode picks a center point (where the center of the object will be) and takes the height. That height is used for the whole object.

Samples a lot of points where the object will cover (horizontally) and picks the highest height, that height is then used to place the object. This mode is useful for preventing any part of your object from being buried though it will float off of cliffs.

Samples only 4 points where the object will cover (horizontally) and picks the highest height, that height is then used to place the object. This mode is useful for preventing any part of your object from being buried though it will float off of cliffs."

Samples a lot of points where the object will cover (horizontally) and picks the lowest height, that height is then used to place the object. This mode is useful for preventing any part of your object from overhanging a cliff though it gets buried a lot

Samples only 4 points where the object will cover (horizontally) and picks the lowest height, that height is then used to place the object. This mode is useful for preventing any part of your object from overhanging a cliff though it gets buried a lot

Stilting is MAX_HEIGHT but it repeats the bottom most block of your object until it hits the surface. This is expensive because it has to first sample every height value for each x,z position of your object. Avoid using this unless its structures for performance reasons.
Just like stilting but very inaccurate. Useful for stilting a lot of objects without too much care on accuracy (you can use the over-stilt value to force stilts under ground further)

Stilting is MIN_HEIGHT but it repeats the bottom most block of your object until it hits the surface. This is expensive because it has to first sample every height value for each x,z position of your object. Avoid using this unless its structures for performance reasons.
Just like MIN_STILT but very inaccurate. Useful for stilting a lot of objects without too much care on accuracy (you can use the over-stilt value to force stilts under ground further)

Stilting is CENTER_HEIGHT but it repeats the bottom most block of your object until it hits the surface. This is expensive because it has to first sample every height value for each x,z position of your object. Avoid using this unless its structures for performance reasons.
Samples the height of the terrain at every x,z position of your object and pushes it down to the surface. It's pretty much like a melt function over the terrain.

oneOf.description: No interpolation. Nearest Neighbor (bad for terrain, great for performance).
Uses 4 nearby points in a square to calculate a 2d slope. Very fast but creates square artifacts. See: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_interpolation

Starcast is Iris's own creation. It uses raytrace checks to find a horizontal boundary nearby. 3 Checks in a circle. Typically starcast is used with another interpolation method. See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.

Starcast is Iris's own creation. It uses raytrace checks to find a horizontal boundary nearby. 6 Checks in a circle. Typically starcast is used with another interpolation method. See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.

Starcast is Iris's own creation. It uses raytrace checks to find a horizontal boundary nearby. 9 Checks in a circle. Typically starcast is used with another interpolation method. See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.

Starcast is Iris's own creation. It uses raytrace checks to find a horizontal boundary nearby. 12 Checks in a circle. Typically starcast is used with another interpolation method. See BILINEAR_STARCAST_9 For example. Starcast is meant to 'break up' large, abrupt cliffs to make cheap interpolation smoother.
Uses starcast to break up the abrupt sharp cliffs, then smooths the rest out with bilinear.

interval.description:
interval
Iris spins the axis but not freely. For example an interval of 90 would mean 4 possible angles (right angles) degrees. 
Setting this to 0 means totally free rotation.

Note that a lot of structures can have issues with non 90 degree intervals because the minecraft block resolution is so low.
   
Number

    
* Default Value is 0.0
* Minimum allowed is 0.0
* Maximum allowed is 360.0
